people showed up.

51
00:02:34,030 --> 00:02:36,970
Several fights then broke out between police
and protesters.

52
00:02:36,970 --> 00:02:38,620
Plus the tear gas.

53
00:02:38,620 --> 00:02:40,440
Police made several arrests.

54
00:02:40,440 --> 00:02:42,660
One of the people arrested was Ventus Lau,

55
00:02:42,660 --> 00:02:44,420
the person who organized the rally.

56
00:02:44,420 --> 00:02:47,580
He’s being charged with, among other things,

57
00:02:47,580 --> 00:02:50,850
“inciting others to take part in an unlawful
assembly.”

58
00:02:50,850 --> 00:02:57,830
Yes, Lau was charged for inciting people to
take part in an unlawful rally...

59
00:02:57,830 --> 00:03:00,700
that police had previously said was totally
lawful

60
00:03:00,700 --> 00:03:03,370
until they changed their minds in the middle
of the rally

61
00:03:03,370 --> 00:03:05,720
and started tear gassing people.

62
00:03:05,720 --> 00:03:09,040
In other words, it was a typical Sunday in
Hong Kong.

63
00:03:09,040 --> 00:03:11,770
But don’t worry, that’s going to change,

64
00:03:11,770 --> 00:03:15,620
thanks to the brilliant minds of Chinese Communist
officials.

65
00:03:15,620 --> 00:03:17,800
The new head of the Liaison Office is pushing

66
00:03:17,800 --> 00:03:21,920
for the Draconian national security law they
tried to pass in 2003.

67
00:03:21,920 --> 00:03:25,630
In 2003, it resulted in massive protests.

68
00:03:25,630 --> 00:03:26,630
So it failed before,

69
00:03:26,630 --> 00:03:29,629
but clearly doing the exact same thing is
going to work this time.

70
00:03:29,629 --> 00:03:34,520
I believe we have a photo of the new head
of the Liaison Office right here.

71
00:03:34,520 --> 00:03:38,030
