as—Canada.

91
00:04:37,340 --> 00:04:39,520
Will she get extradited to the US?

92
00:04:39,520 --> 00:04:43,389
Well, extradition hearings have begun, but
that’s just the beginning.

93
00:04:43,389 --> 00:04:47,449
“This week's hearing focuses on whether
Meng's alleged crimes in the U.S.

94
00:04:47,449 --> 00:04:49,389
are also illegal in Canada.

95
00:04:49,389 --> 00:04:53,400
Meng's defense say the central issue is so
called "double criminality",

96
00:04:53,400 --> 00:04:56,950
as in, charges she is accused in the U.S.

97
00:04:56,950 --> 00:04:59,590
must also be considered crimes in Canada.

98
00:04:59,590 --> 00:05:04,120
Meng's lawyers argue the case is founded on
allegations of breaching

99
00:05:04,120 --> 00:05:05,699
U.S. sanctions against Iran.

100
00:05:05,699 --> 00:05:08,699
But, Canada has rejected those same sanctions.

101
00:05:08,699 --> 00:05:11,200
So, they argue Meng can't be extradited.”

102
00:05:11,200 --> 00:05:14,610
And legal experts say it could be years before
a decision is reached.

103
00:05:14,610 --> 00:05:18,120
So Meng will remain in legal limbo in Canada.

104
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:20,590
Don’t feel too bad for her, though.

105
00:05:20,590 --> 00:05:23,250
Her “prison cell” is house arrest.

106
00:05:23,250 --> 00:05:25,880
At her 12-million-dollar luxury home.

107
00:05:25,880 --> 00:05:29,490
Plus, she’s getting by with a little help
from her friends.

108
00:05:29,490 --> 00:05:33,949
